ThoughtMap v0.1

ThoughtMap is an experimental project that visualizes thought patterns hidden within song lyrics.

Originally created from a dataset of 992 self-written songs, the project explores whether lyrics can be used to understand how a person thinks, what themes they repeatedly return to, and how their worldview evolves over time.

Core Concept

Instead of classifying songs by traditional genres such as love, rock, pop, or jazz, ThoughtMap analyzes lyrics based on recurring patterns of thought.

Examples include:

Society
Cognition
Experimentation
Causality
Introspection
Philosophy
Technology

The goal is not to classify music, but to map the structure of thought itself.

Current Features
1. Lyric Embedding

Converts lyrics into vector representations using language embeddings.

2. Similarity Search

Find songs that are semantically close to a given lyric or idea.

3. Thought Clustering

Groups songs into recurring philosophical and thematic domains.

4. Thought Continent Visualization

Displays songs and cluster centers on a shared semantic map.

5. Civilization Profile

Aggregates clusters into higher-level "civilizations" and calculates their distribution.

6. Thought Search Engine

Search for ideas such as:

Algorithm criticism
Subjectivity
Failure
Community dependency
Capitalism criticism

and discover related works.

Current Workflow

Lyrics

↓

Embedding

↓

Similarity Search

↓

Clustering

↓

Thought Continent

↓

Civilization Profile

↓

Thought Search

Future Roadmap

Planned features include:

Multi-author comparison
Similar thinker discovery
Automatic cluster naming using AI
New song diagnosis
Timeline analysis
Web application
Public search engine
Long-Term Vision

ThoughtMap aims to become a search engine for ideas.

Users will be able to:

Upload lyrics or writing
Discover their own thought profile
Compare themselves with other creators
Find people with similar thinking patterns
Explore niche and common themes

The project treats creative works not only as art, but also as traces of cognition.
